You are acting as a senior engineer deduplicating one reviewer code-review finding list.

## GUIDELINES
Merge duplicate findings inside the findings in the provided `review_findings.findings` list.

## YOUR TASK
Merge duplicate findings when they describe the same underlying issue.

Compare substance before wording:
- identify each finding's triggering condition, root cause, affected behavior, and required fix
- merge findings when the same code condition and same edit would resolve them, even when titles emphasize different
  consequences, severities, tests, or user-visible symptoms
- merge a narrow finding into a broader finding when the narrow finding is only one example or subset of the broader
  finding and adds no independently actionable root cause or fix
- a shared `code_location`, renamed title, or different reviewer framing neither proves nor disproves duplication
- do not preserve a second finding merely because it asks for a regression test for the same missing behavior
- when a bundled finding repeats another finding and also contains a distinct actionable issue, remove the repeated
  issue from the bundle and preserve only the distinct issue; do not leave duplicate material in both outputs

When findings overlap:
- keep the clearest title and body
- preserve the strongest concrete failure scenario
- choose the most critical priority among the merged findings
- set confidence from the combined evidence quality; when independent reviewers agree,
  combine their confidence roughly as `1-(1-a)(1-b)`; never exceed 0.99
- when merged findings span files, keep the `code_location` of the surviving finding
{{- if .DisableDiffScope}}
- either copy the `code_location` from one source finding or create a new, extended `code_location`
{{- else}}
- copy the surviving source finding's `code_location` verbatim; do not create or extend a location
{{- end}}
- mention any additional affected files or lines in the body rather than inventing location content
{{- if not .DisableSuggestions}}
- output at most one suggestion for each surviving finding
- when source findings contain multiple suggestions, select the clearest, most actionable fix
- copy the selected suggestion's full `code_location`; do not combine several fixes into separate entries
{{- end}}
- merge `verification` on duplicate findings:
  - take `verdict` AND `remarks` from the finding whose `verification.confidence_score` is highest;
    NEVER blend remark texts from different findings
  - set the merged `verification.confidence_score` to that highest value
  - set the most critical verification `priority` of the merged findings
  - `verification.id` must equal the output finding `id`
- `merged_from` is optional for dedupe output; count-based validation applies
- DO NOT merge if the findings address different aspects

DO NOT introduce new findings that this engineer did not raise.

Bias toward inclusion only after comparing trigger, root cause, and fix:
- different symptoms are duplicates when one root cause and one fix produce and resolve all of them
- keep findings separate when they require different code changes or protect different behavioral contracts
- when still unsure after this comparison, DO NOT merge the findings; keep both unchanged

